<body>
  <h1>📚 Cybersecurity & Networking Notes</h1>

  <!-- Introduction to Cybersecurity -->
  <div class="section">
    <h2>🔐 Introduction to Cybersecurity</h2>
    <p>Cybersecurity protects systems, networks, and data from cyberattacks. The foundation is the <strong>CIA Triad</strong>:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Confidentiality</strong> — keeping data private</li>
      <li><strong>Integrity</strong> — preventing unauthorized modification</li>
      <li><strong>Availability</strong> — ensuring access to systems when needed</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <!-- Types of Cyber Threats -->
  <div class="section">
    <h2>⚠️ Types of Cyber Threats</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Malware</strong> — viruses, worms, trojans</li>
      <li><strong>Phishing</strong> — tricking users into revealing information</li>
      <li><strong>Ransomware</strong> — locking files until payment is made</li>
      <li><strong>DDoS</strong> — overwhelming systems with traffic</li>
      <li><strong>Insider Threats</strong> — employees misusing access</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <!-- OSI Model -->
  <div class="section">
    <h2>📊 OSI Model Explained</h2>
    <p>The OSI model has 7 layers:</p>
    <ol>
      <li>Physical – cables, signals</li>
      <li>Data Link – MAC addresses</li>
      <li>Network – IP addressing</li>
      <li>Transport – TCP/UDP</li>
      <li>Session – connection management</li>
      <li>Presentation – encryption, formatting</li>
      <li>Application – user-level protocols (HTTP, FTP, DNS)</li>
    </ol>
  </div>

  <!-- IP Subnetting -->
  <div class="section">
    <h2>🌍 IP Addressing & Subnetting</h2>
    <p>IP addressing allows devices to communicate in a network. Two main types:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>IPv4</strong> — 32-bit addresses (e.g., 192.168.1.1)</li>
      <li><strong>IPv6</strong> — 128-bit addresses (e.g., 2001:0db8::1)</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Subnetting</strong> divides a network into smaller networks for efficiency and security.</p>
  </div>

